Yes, you can absolutely add that. To make players adaptive, give each player a dictionary tracking opponent history (opponent name -> list of their last N moves). For the CopyCat bot, instead of blindly copying the opponent's last move, you calculate which move *beats* that move. So if RockBot plays ROCK, CopyCat updates its internal logic to play PAPER next time against RockBot.

Here’s how that core change looks:

class MemoryPlayer(Player):
    def __init__(self, name, strategy=None):
        super().__init__(name, strategy)
        self.history = {}  # opponent_name -> list of moves

    def record_result(self, opponent, move_played):
        if opponent.name not in self.history:
            self.history[opponent.name] = []
        self.history[opponent.name].append(move_played)
        if len(self.history[opponent.name]) > 5:
            self.history[opponent.name].pop(0)

class CounterStrategy(Player):
    def play(self):
        # If we know opponent played ROCK last time, play PAPER
        if 'RockBot' in self.history and self.history['RockBot'][-1] == Move.ROCK:
            return Move.PAPER
        # Otherwise fall back to random
        return random.choice(list(Move))

You’d pass this new `CounterStrategy` instance to your players. In the Arena, call `player.record_result(opponent, result)` after every match so the memory updates before the next round.

